                <head>192. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On June 28, 1962, <persName corresp="#p_SAEII1">Adlai Stevenson</persName> sent
                    President <persName corresp="#p_KJF2">Kennedy</persName> a 6-page letter on
                    current disarmament problems. The letter is printed in full in <hi rend="italic"
                        >The Papers of <persName corresp="#p_SAEII1">Adlai E. Stevenson</persName>:
                        Ambassador to the United Nations, 1961-1965</hi>, volume VIII, pages
                    265-269. Attached to a copy of the letter in the <persName corresp="#p_KJF2"
                        >Kennedy</persName> Library is a June 29 memorandum from <persName
                        corresp="#p_SAMJ1">Arthur Schlesinger, Jr.</persName> to <persName
                        corresp="#p_KC2">Carl Kaysen</persName> that reads, “You may wish to
                    consider the attached letter from Governor <persName corresp="#p_SAEII1"
                        >Stevenson</persName>—and also how best to answer it.” (<persName
                        corresp="#p_KJF2">Kennedy</persName> Library, National Security Files,
                    Kaysen Series, Disarmament, General, 6/61-12/62) No response to the letter has
                    been found.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
